// ATTACK SURFACE MAP TEMPLATE:
//
// === URLS FOUND ===
// /welcome — login page (public)
// /account — user profile (authenticated)
// /transfer — fund transfer (authenticated)
// /balance — customer list (admin only?)
// /logout — session destruction
//
// === FORMS FOUND ===
// Login: [username] [password] → POST /welcome
// Profile: [description] → POST /account
// Transfer: [to] [transferAmount] → POST /transfer
// Upload: [profilePic] → POST /account (multipart)
//
// === COOKIES ===
// JSESSIONID — session cookie
// Flags: HttpOnly=? Secure=? SameSite=?
//
// === HIDDEN ELEMENTS ===
// HTML comments: <!-- TODO: remove debug -->
// JavaScript files: Account.js, Transfer.js
// Hidden form fields: none found / csrf_token?

// SYSTEMATIC INPUT TESTING:
// Field: Login password
// Test 1: ' → Error? SQL error message? → SQLi possible
// Test 2: ' OR '1'='1' -- → Logged in? → SQLi confirmed
// Test 3: <script>alert(1)</script> → Alert? → XSS
// Test 4: admin'; DROP TABLE users;-- → Don't try this first!

// Field: Profile description
// Test 1: <b>bold</b> → Shows bold text? → HTML injection
// Test 2: <script>alert('XSS')</script> → Alert? → Stored XSS!
// Test 3: <img src=x onerror=alert(1)> → Alert? → XSS bypass

// Field: Transfer 'to' field
// Test 1: abc (non-numeric) → Error handling?
// Test 2: -100 (negative) → Logic flaw?
// Test 3: 999999999999 (overflow) → Integer overflow?

// COOKIE INSPECTION CHECKLIST:
//
// Open F12 → Storage tab → Cookies
// Find JSESSIONID:
//
// ┌────────────┬───────────┬──────────┬────────────┐
// │ Name       │ Value     │ HttpOnly │ Secure     │
// ├────────────┼───────────┼──────────┼────────────┤
// │ JSESSIONID │ node0abc  │ false ✗  │ false ✗    │
// └────────────┴───────────┴──────────┴────────────┘
//
// Findings:
// ✗ HttpOnly=false → CWE-1004 → JS can steal cookie
// ✗ Secure=false → CWE-614 → sent over plain HTTP
// ✗ SameSite=none → CSRF possible
//
// TEST: document.cookie in console
// If JSESSIONID appears → HttpOnly is NOT set → VULNERABLE

// ACCESS CONTROL TEST MATRIX:
//
// URL             | Admin  | User1  | User2  | No auth
// ────────────────┼────────┼────────┼────────┼────────
// /account        | Own ✓  | Own ✓  | Own ✓  | → login
// /account?u=user2| user2  | user2? | Own    | → login
// /balance        | All ✓  | All?   | All?   | → login
// /transfer       | ✓      | ✓      | ✓      | → login
//
// If User1 can access /balance → CWE-862 (Missing Auth)
// If User1 sees user2 data via URL → CWE-639 (IDOR)
//
// HOW TO TEST:
// 1. Login as user1
// 2. Note your URLs and what you can see
// 3. Try admin URLs (just type them in the address bar)
// 4. Try other users' URLs (change username parameter)

// CSRF TEST — Transfer form:
// Step 1: Inspect the form HTML
// <form action='/transfer' method='POST'>
//   <input name='to' type='text'>
//   <input name='transferAmount' type='text'>
//   <button>Transfer</button>
// </form>
// No csrf_token field → VULNERABLE!

// Step 2: Create attack page (csrf_test.html):
// <html><body>
// <form action='http://localhost:15000/transfer' method='POST'>
//   <input type='hidden' name='to' value='999999'>
//   <input type='hidden' name='transferAmount' value='100'>
// </form>
// <script>document.forms[0].submit();</script>
// </body></html>

// Step 3: Open csrf_test.html while logged in
// If transfer succeeds → CSRF confirmed!

// ERROR HANDLING TESTS:
//
// Test 1: Single quote in login
// Input: admin / '
// Result: 'SQL error: near "'": syntax error'
// Finding: CWE-209 — SQL query structure exposed!
//
// Test 2: Non-existent URL
// Visit: /nonexistentpage
// Result: Jetty 500 error with full stack trace
// Finding: CWE-209 — Server version + class names exposed!
//
// Test 3: View HTML source (Ctrl+U)
// Found: <!-- TODO: remove before production -->
// Found: <!-- Admin panel at /admin/debug -->
// Finding: CWE-615 — Sensitive comments in HTML!
//
// Test 4: Check response headers (F12 → Network)
// Server: Jetty(9.4.z-SNAPSHOT)
// Finding: Server version disclosed in headers!

// VULNERABILITY DOCUMENTATION TEMPLATE:
//
// Name: Stored Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)
// CWE: CWE-79
// OWASP: A03:2021 Injection
// Location: Profile description field (/account)
// Severity: HIGH
//
// Description:
// The profile description field stores user input without
// sanitisation and renders it without encoding.
//
// Steps to reproduce:
// 1. Login as admin
// 2. Enter <script>alert('XSS')</script> in profile
// 3. Save profile
// 4. Refresh page → alert executes
//
// Evidence: [screenshot of alert popup]
//
// CIA Impact:
// Confidentiality: HIGH — session cookies stolen
// Integrity: HIGH — profiles modified, funds transferred
// Availability: LOW — page manipulation possible
//
// Reference: https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html

// QUICK TEST — 5 vulnerabilities in under 10 minutes:
//
// Test 1 (SQLi): Login with ' as password
//   → SQL error? → CWE-89
//
// Test 2 (XSS): Enter <script>alert(1)</script> in any text field
//   → Alert popup? → CWE-79
//
// Test 3 (CSRF): Inspect transfer form source
//   → No csrf_token? → CWE-352
//
// Test 4 (Session): F12 → Storage → Cookies
//   → HttpOnly=false? → CWE-1004
//
// Test 5 (Access): Try admin URLs as normal user
//   → Page loads? → CWE-862
//
// Each test takes about 2 minutes.
// Total: ~10 minutes for 5 potential vulnerabilities.

// CWE LOOKUP CHEAT SHEET:
//
// Found this?             → It's this CWE:
// ─────────────────────────────────────────
// ' causes SQL error      → CWE-89
// <script> executes       → CWE-79
// ; ls shows files        → CWE-78
// ../ reads other files   → CWE-22
// No CSRF token           → CWE-352
// HttpOnly missing        → CWE-1004
// Secure missing          → CWE-614
// Stack trace shown       → CWE-209
// User sees admin page    → CWE-862
// User sees other's data  → CWE-639
// Login with ' OR '1'='1  → CWE-89
//
// Full database: https://cwe.mitre.org/
// OWASP Top 10: https://owasp.org/Top10/

// CIA ASSESSMENT EXAMPLES:
//
// SQL Injection:
// C: CRITICAL — read any user's data
// I: CRITICAL — modify/delete records, DROP TABLE
// A: HIGH — can destroy the database
// Overall: CRITICAL
//
// Stored XSS:
// C: HIGH — steal session cookies
// I: HIGH — modify page content, transfer funds
// A: LOW — can redirect users but service stays up
// Overall: HIGH
//
// Missing HttpOnly:
// C: HIGH — session cookie readable by JS
// I: LOW — doesn't directly enable modification
// A: LOW — no availability impact
// Overall: MEDIUM (enables other attacks)
//
// Information Disclosure:
// C: MEDIUM — server version, class names exposed
// I: LOW — no modification possible
// A: LOW — no disruption
// Overall: LOW (but helps attacker plan other attacks)

// REPORT TEMPLATE — FILL IN FOR EACH VULNERABILITY:
//
// === VULNERABILITY #X ===
// Title: CWE-XX — [Name]
// Severity: HIGH
// Location: /account page, profile description field
//
// Description:
// [2-3 sentences explaining the vulnerability]
//
// Steps to reproduce:
// 1. Navigate to [URL]
// 2. Enter [specific input] in [specific field]
// 3. Click [button]
// 4. Observe [what happens]
//
// Evidence:
// [Screenshot 1: input entered]
// [Screenshot 2: result/impact]
//
// Impact on CIA:
// Confidentiality: [HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW] — [why]
// Integrity: [HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW] — [why]
// Availability: [HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW] — [why]
//
// Reference:
// https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/XX.html
// OWASP: A0X:2021 — [Category name]

// BROWSER DEVTOOLS — YOUR BEST FRIEND:
//
// F12 → Network tab:
// 1. Submit a form
// 2. Click the new request entry
// 3. See: URL, method, parameters, cookies, response
// 4. Right-click → Copy as cURL (gives you the exact command!)
//
// F12 → Console tab:
// 1. Type: document.cookie
// 2. See all accessible cookies
// 3. Type: document.forms[0]
// 4. See the first form's structure
//
// F12 → Elements tab:
// 1. Right-click any element → Inspect
// 2. See the HTML structure
// 3. Look for hidden inputs, CSRF tokens
// 4. Check if values are HTML-encoded or raw
//
// CTRL+U: View full page source
// Look for: comments, hidden fields, JS files, API endpoints

